## 1. Purpose
This policy establishes [COMPANY]'s implementation of the HIPAA **minimum necessary** standard: when using, disclosing, or requesting PHI, [COMPANY] makes reasonable efforts to limit PHI to the minimum reasonably necessary to accomplish the intended purpose (45 CFR §§ 164.502(b), 164.514(d)). It ties the standard to [COMPANY]'s role-based access controls so the principle is enforced technically, not just on paper.

## 2. Scope
Applies to all uses, disclosures, and requests of PHI by all workforce members, contractors, and in-scope systems (production SaaS application, [AWS environment], [Snowflake], [GitHub] CI/CD), in any form. It applies to internal access to PHI as well as disclosures to and requests from third parties.

## 3. Policy
1. Workforce members **shall** access, use, disclose, and request only the PHI **minimally necessary** to perform their job function or the purpose at hand.
2. [COMPANY] **shall** identify the workforce roles that need access to PHI, the categories of PHI each role needs, and the conditions of access, and **shall** restrict access accordingly per `../access/access-control-policy.md.template` (role-based access control / least privilege).
3. For **routine, recurring** uses and disclosures, [COMPANY] **shall** implement **standard protocols** that limit PHI to the minimum necessary, so each instance is not separately evaluated (§ 164.514(d)(3)).
4. For **non-routine** disclosures and requests, [COMPANY] **shall** evaluate each on its own criteria and limit PHI to the minimum necessary; the [Privacy Officer] reviews where the determination is unclear.
5. When **requesting** PHI from another covered entity or business associate, [COMPANY] **shall** request no more than the minimum necessary for the purpose.
6. [COMPANY] **may reasonably rely** on a requested disclosure as the minimum necessary when the requestor is a public official, another covered entity, a professional within [COMPANY], or a researcher with appropriate documentation, where such reliance is reasonable (§ 164.514(d)(3)(iii)).
7. A request or disclosure of an **entire medical record** **shall not** be made unless the entire record is specifically justified as the minimum necessary for the purpose.
8. Where [COMPANY] is a **Business Associate**, minimum necessary **shall** be applied consistent with the BAA and the Covered Entity's instructions.

## 4. Exceptions — Where Minimum Necessary Does NOT Apply
The minimum necessary standard does **not** apply to the following (45 CFR § 164.502(b)(2)). Workforce **shall** still apply all other access and authorization controls, but **shall not** withhold or truncate PHI in these cases:
1. Disclosures to or requests by a **health care provider for treatment**.
2. Uses or disclosures made **to the individual** who is the subject of the PHI.
3. Uses or disclosures made pursuant to a **valid authorization** by the individual.
4. Disclosures made to **HHS** for Privacy Rule compliance, enforcement, or investigation.
5. Uses or disclosures **required by law**.
6. Uses or disclosures required for **compliance with the HIPAA Administrative Simplification Rules**.

## 5. Role-Based Access Tie-In
1. PHI access in [AWS environment] and [Snowflake] **shall** be granted via defined roles/groups mapped to job functions, not to named individuals ad hoc.
2. [Snowflake] access **shall** use role hierarchy, secure views, row/column-level security, and dynamic data masking so analysts see only the PHI fields and rows their role requires; de-identified or limited data sets **shall** be used where full PHI is not needed (see `de-identification-and-limited-data-set.md.template`).
3. Access **shall** be reviewed at least [quarterly] and on role change/termination per `../access/access-control-policy.md.template` and `../access/access-recertification-procedure.md.template`.
4. Standing access to production PHI **shall** be minimized; just-in-time / break-glass access **shall** be logged and reviewed.

## 6. Roles & Responsibilities
| Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| [Privacy Officer] | Owns this policy; defines standard protocols; rules on non-routine and unclear determinations. |
| [Security Officer] | Implements and enforces role-based access controls realizing minimum necessary; monitors access. |
| Data/Role Owners | Define which PHI categories each role needs; approve access requests. |
| All Workforce | Access and disclose only the minimum necessary PHI for their task. |

See `../governance/roles-and-responsibilities.md.template` for full role definitions.

## 7. Exceptions
Process exceptions (distinct from the regulatory exceptions in §4) require documented risk acceptance per `../governance/exceptions-and-waivers.md.template`, approved by the [Privacy Officer], time-bound, and recorded in the exceptions log.

## 8. Compliance, Monitoring & Enforcement
Compliance is monitored through access reviews, query/disclosure log analysis (e.g., [Snowflake] access history), and audits of standard protocols. Excessive or unnecessary access is investigated and remediated. Violations are handled per `../people/hr-security-policy.md.template` and the HIPAA workforce sanctions process (`sanctions-policy.md.template`).

